奇:["大: large; St Bernard (RTK)　可: can","strange","UNUSUAL, odd","I find it<strong> strange</strong> that so many people commit suicide in Tokyo by throwing themselves in front of the train. To me when I look at this kanji, I see a train just about to come out of a tunnel, and above the man waiting for his oppourtunity where he can end it all.","Imagine a ST. BERNARD DOG carrying a CAN instead of a barrel in rescue missions. How<strong> strange</strong>!","キ","く.しき、 あや.しい、 くし、 めずら.しい","奇 【キ】 strange, unconventional<br>奇麗 【キレイ】 pretty, lovely, beautiful, fair, clean, clear, pure, tidy, neat, completely, entirely<br>数奇 【スウキ】 misfortune, adverse fortune, hapless fate, unfortunate (e.g. life), checkered, varied<br>好奇 【コウキ】 inquisitiveness","奇しき 【くしき】 strange, mysterious, queer<br>奇しくも 【くしくも】 strangely, oddly, miraculously, mysteriously<br>奇しき 【くしき】 strange, mysterious, queer"],
川:["巛: river (川); flood (RTK)","stream","RIVER","So as not to confuse this with <a href=\"/study/kanji/%E6%B2%B3\">河</a> (<span class=\"frnr\">#157</span>) think of<strong> stream</strong>ers falling down.","There are <em>three</em> default I/O <strong>Streams</strong> in UNIX, stdin, stdout, and stderr.","セン","かわ","川柳 【センリュウ】 senryu, comic haiku, humorous seventeen-syllable poem<br>川きゅう 【センキュウ】 cnidium rhizome (Cnidium officinale)<br>河川 【カセン】 rivers<br>山川 【サンセン】 mountains and rivers","川 【かわ】 river, stream, the .... river, (suffix used with the names of rivers)<br>川沿い 【かわぞい】 along the river, riverside<br>天の川 【あまのがわ】 Milky Way<br>三途の川 【さんずのかわ】 Sanzu River (Buddhist equivalent of the River Styx)"],
州:["巛: river (川); flood (RTK)　丶: dot; drop　丶: dot; drop　丶: dot; drop","state","STATE, province　SANDBAR","There were 3 little islands in the <em>stream</em> who all decided to set themselves up as independent <strong>states</strong>.","シュウ　The original meaning of this character was \"sandbar\", and for me this conjures up images of the Mississippi River, which is very wide with many sandbars and which was used to define the borders in ten American<strong> state</strong>s. Picture Huck Finn and Tom Sawyer floating by<strong> state</strong> after<strong> state</strong> as they adventure down the mighty Mississippi, occasionally beaching their raft on sandbars.","シュウ、 ス","す","州 【シュウ】 state, province, county, oblast, department (of ancient China), continent, (after someone's name) dear<br>州都 【シュウト】 state capital, provincial capital, county town<br>本州 【ホンシュウ】 Honshu (largest of the four main islands of Japan)<br>欧州 【オウシュウ】 Europe<br>州 【ス】 sandbank, sandbar<br>洲浜 【スハマ】 sandy beach, sandbar that projects into the ocean, particularly in a wavy form, designs and objects with a wavy pattern, sweet mochi cake<br>白州 【シラス】 bar of white sand, gravel separating a noh stage from the audience, court of law(in the Edo period)<br>中州 【ナカス】 sandbank (in a river), sandbar","州 【す】 sandbank, sandbar<br>洲浜 【すはま】 sandy beach, sandbar that projects into the ocean, particularly in a wavy form, designs and objects with a wavy pattern, sweet mochi cake<br>白州 【しらす】 bar of white sand, gravel separating a noh stage from the audience, court of law(in the Edo period)<br>中州 【なかす】 sandbank (in a river), sandbar"],
