牢:["宀: house (RTK)　牛: cow (⺧)","jail","PRISON　HARDNESS","For a <em>cow</em> used to free-grazing, being stuck in a <em>house</em> is equivalent to being in<strong> jail</strong>.","Looking at the kanji 家, keeping pigs in the house was normal. But, if you instead kept a <em>cow</em> in the <em>house</em>, you would be sent to <strong>jail</strong>.","ロウ","かた.い、 ひとや","牢 【ロウ】 prison, jail, gaol<br>牢獄 【ロウゴク】 prison, jail, gaol<br>堅牢 【ケンロウ】 solid<br>永牢 【エイロウ】 life imprisonment",""],
宋:["","Sung dynasty","","The<strong> Sung dynasty</strong> was so-called because people kept <em>trees</em> in their <em>houses</em> and as a consequence birds <strong>sung</strong> in them.","The<strong> Sung dynasty</strong> needed to cut down a lot of TREES to make a lot of HOUSES. (the imperial dynasty of China from 960 to 1279; noted for art and literature and philosophy).","ソウ","","宋 【ソウ】 Song (dynasty of China)<br>宋音 【ソウオン】 T'ang reading of Chinese characters<br>北宋 【ホクソウ】 Northern Song (dynasty of China)<br>入宋 【ニッソウ】 journeying to Sung China during the Heian and Kamakura periods",""],
宍:["","venison","","I was once served<strong> venison</strong> at <em>home</em>, but the only way I could eat it was to down a <em>six</em> pack first.","I told my friend the deer I kept in my <em>house</em> for<strong> venison</strong> was called \"roku\" (<em>six</em>). He asked if naming it didn't make me attached to it. I said no, because \"roku\" is also a way to say the kanji for deer.","ニク、 ジク","しし","肉 【ニク】 flesh, meat, the physical body (as opposed to the spirit), thickness, ink pad","肉 【にく】 flesh, meat, the physical body (as opposed to the spirit), thickness, ink pad<br>膂宍 【そしし】 meat, flesh, or muscles along the spine"],
屠:["","butchering","","Generals usually see their soldiers as mere <em>puppets</em> in their war game. These poor sods are given a <em>flag</em> and told to fight for their country. As if that would make good all the<strong> butchering</strong>.","Flag, lovedoll: My first suspicion was mitigated since my <em>lovedoll</em> was still giving me good lovin'. But when I noticed that little <em>flag</em> which had suddenly appeared on her left breast, I knew something was wrong. Checking her diary, I find out that a <em>lovedoll</em> coup was underway, which would involve<strong> butchering</strong> all owners!","ト、 チョ","ほふ.る","屠殺 【トサツ】 slaughter (of animals for meat)<br>屠殺場 【トサツジョウ】 abattoir<br>浮屠 【フト】 Buddha, stupa, Buddhist temple, Buddhist monk","屠る 【ほふる】 to slaughter, to massacre, to defeat, to butcher"],
屁:["","fart","","You haven't smelled a <strong>fart</strong> like his! His were so bad, that when he cut one, they had to wave a <em>flag</em> to keep folks away. None <em>compare</em> to the <strong>fart</strong>s that he <strong>fart</strong>s.","At a<strong> fart</strong> contest each contestant holds up a <em>flag</em> whenever they<strong> fart</strong> so the judges can come over and <em>compare</em> it to the others.","ヒ","へ、 おなら","放屁 【ホウヒ】 breaking wind, fart","屁 【おなら】 wind, gas, fart, something worthless, something not worth considering<br>屁糞葛 【へくそかずら】 skunkvine (Paederia foetida), stinkvine, Chinese fever vine<br>河童の屁 【かっぱのへ】 something easy to do, cinch<br>屁 【おなら】 wind, gas, fart, something worthless, something not worth considering"],
屑:["尸: corpse; flag (RTK)　肖: resemblance; spark, candle (RTK)","rubbish","SCRAPS, scum","You aren't supposed to throw an American <em>flag</em> out with the<strong> rubbish</strong>. The proper way to get rid of a flag is to burn it, shown here by holding a <em>candle</em> underneath it.","Japanese society has always been quite environmentally conscious. Even back in the Edo period, they had an ingenious method for punishing people that didn't properly separate their<strong> rubbish</strong>. If, for example, you threw your ペットボトル into the paper can, a large <em>Semaphore Flag</em> would fly up out of nowhere and alert people, and a <em>candle</em> would fly out of the can and catch you on fire, so that people would know immediately who the perpetrator was.","セツ","くず、 いさぎよ.い","鋸屑 【ノコクズ】 sawdust<br>鱗屑 【リンセツ】 scale (i.e. of pathologically dry skin)","屑 【くず】 waste, scrap, garbage, dregs, chad<br>屑籠 【くずかご】 waste basket, wastepaper basket<br>紙屑 【かみくず】 wastepaper, paper scraps, paper waste<br>藻屑 【もくず】 scraps of seaweed, death at sea (metaphor)"],
