鑓:["","javelin","","A<strong> javelin</strong> is a piece of <em>metal</em> used for <em>dispatching</em> enemies – or athletics judges if they’re not careful.","What was not reported in RtK1 is that it was with a<strong> javelin</strong> that finally they were able to 遣 <a href=\"/study/kanji/%E9%81%A3\">遣</a> (<span class=\"frnr\">#1910</span>) the <em>conductor</em> who had dropped his baton as he ran down the <em>road</em> with that lady's <em>purse</em>. It was an amazing throw, from a remarkable distance, worthy of a <em>gold</em> medal if it had been the Olympics instead of a crime scene.","","やり","","槍 【やり】 spear, lance, javelin, lance (shogi piece), jeering"],
鋒:["","sword’s point","","A <em>pointy</em> (see my explanation in 峰 <a href=\"/study/kanji/%E5%B3%B0\">峰</a> (<span class=\"frnr\">#1683</span>)) bit of <em>metal</em> is a <strong>sword's point</strong>.","A <em>metal</em> sword's point is pointed at the lovers having a <em>tryst</em>. Looks like someone got caught!","ホウ","きっさき、 とかり、 ほこさき","切っ先 【キッサキ】 point (of a sword, etc.), pointed verbal attack<br>蜂起 【ホウキ】 uprising, revolt<br>鋭鋒 【エイホウ】 brunt of attack or argument<br>兵鋒 【ヘイホウ】 the point of a sword, the advance of an army","切っ先 【きっさき】 point (of a sword, etc.), pointed verbal attack<br>矛 【ほこ】 long-handled Chinese spear, lance, pike, weapon, arms, grip of a bow<br>矛先 【ほこさき】 point of spear, spearhead, brunt, aim of attack, force of argument"],
鎚:["","hammer","","The<strong> hammer</strong> is the same as the <a href=\"/study/kanji/%E6%A7%8C\">槌</a> (<span class=\"frnr\">#2543</span>), except it's made out of <em>metal</em>.","The <em>maestro</em> grabs a <em>metal</em><strong> hammer</strong> to get back at those <em>chasing</em> him down the <em>road</em>.","ツイ、 タイ","つち","鉄槌 【テッツイ】 iron hammer, crushing blow",""],
鉦:["","carillion","","The church<strong> carillion</strong> was composed of <em>metal</em> bells that informed when it was the <em>correct</em> time to go to church.","Wtf is a<strong> carillion</strong>? How about \"gong\" instead. Picture a game show where they bang on the gong every time you get the correct answer. Or, if you want to go with the book explanation,<strong> carillion</strong> is the \"western\" bell which is struck from the inside rather than outside. Story: just like everything else in the East (writing, utensils, etc) bells are harder to work than necessary, being hit from the outside and all. The correct way is to put the gong on the inside, makes it so much easier.","セイ、 ショウ","かね","鉦 【カネ】 gong, handbell<br>鉦鼓 【ショウコ】 small gong (used in gagaku)","鉦 【かね】 gong, handbell"],
